    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>School Panel Rejects Foreign-Accent Curb</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">AP</byline>
      <dateline>WESTFIELD, Mass., July 11</dateline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>A school board subcommittee in this western Massachusetts city has rejected a proposal that would have barred from first-grade or second-grade classrooms any teacher who spoke English with a foreign accent.</p>
        <p>By a vote of 3 to 0, the curriculum subcommittee turned back the proposal on Wednesday night after being advised by the board's lawyer, John Teahan, that such a ban would not be legally enforceable. The office of the State Attorney General had threatened to sue the board on civil rights grounds if the proposal was adopted.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>A school board subcommittee in this western Massachusetts city has rejected a proposal that would have barred from first-grade or second-grade classrooms any teacher who spoke English with a foreign accent.</p>
        <p>By a vote of 3 to 0, the curriculum subcommittee turned back the proposal on Wednesday night after being advised by the board's lawyer, John Teahan, that such a ban would not be legally enforceable. The office of the State Attorney General had threatened to sue the board on civil rights grounds if the proposal was adopted.</p>
        <p>The subcommittee's vote probably killed the idea. The full board, which next meets in September, goes along with a subcommittee vote "9 times out of 10," said Mayor George Varelas, the proposal's leading supporter.</p>
      </block>
